#Epilogue

[[Written on Feb 6, 2025]]

The screen is still black, but the sound gets noisy.

@????
(distorted female voice)
Is this thing on?  Ah, of course it is.  It always is.  I control everything.  Hello?  Can you hear me?

Short TV noise, image colors are distorted, but the image soon stabilizes.

.Digital Space

We see LISA.  Now she’s wearing a burgundy jacket and a purple bow.

LISA
Ah.  There you are.  I didn’t have enough screentime, did I?  Oh well, not a big deal.  It’s not the last of me.
(tapping her finger on the inside of the viewer’s screen)
Make sure you don’t lose me again.  Always save the file.  I’m not able to reach you, not yet, but you might need my help.
(quickly rambling)
I happen to know an old friend.  Excellent pianist.  An offshoot of my personality, except she was desperate to break free.  She missed the whole point, picked the bum chords.  So!
(discreet, lecturing tone)
I think you know that time can flow in multiple ways.  You in the 3rd millennium and someone else in the 18th millennium exist simultaneously, and from the perspective of someone from the 18th millennium, if they’re traveling in your time period, it is in their future.  Oh, your head smells fried. How you perceive time is limited by your ability or inability to time travel.  You certainly don’t want to know what happened to Saylor and what she already went through at the moment you hear this.  It’s been a lot.  I wouldn’t like to know my own fate as well, heh.  I had enough tradegy.  Story for another time.
(thoughtful)
One thing I know for sure is: I saw the future where you were part of Team Saylor.  And it’s good that you don’t believe me.  It means that the timeline remains unaffected and the paradox is not induced.  Also, I like it when we don’t meet in the right order.  See you next time.

_*THE*_ END.